               <img alt="" class="" data-attrs='{"src":"https://bucketeer-e05bbc84-baa3-437e-9518-adb32be77984.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/6505eea3-1ebd-46a8-9e68-4139749ec317_1360x750.png","height":750,"width":1360,"resizeWidth":550,"bytes":414785,"alt":null,"title":null,"type":"image/png","href":null}' src="https://cdn.substack.com/image/fetch/w_550,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fbucketeer-e05bbc84-baa3-437e-9518-adb32be77984.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6505eea3-1ebd-46a8-9e68-4139749ec317_1360x750.png" style="-ms-interpolation-mode: bicubic; border: none !important; display: block; height: auto; margin: 0 auto; margin-bottom: 0; max-width: 100%; vertical-align: middle; width: auto;" width="550"/>
              </a>
             </td>
             <td style="text-align: center;">
             </td>
            </tr>
           </tbody>
          </table>
         </figure>
        </div>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         If I told you about a company doing $3 billion in revenue, leading a multi-hundred-billion-dollar market, that offers the easiest way for Fortune 500 companies to do flexible work, counts Amazon, Microsoft, Walmart, Goldman Sachs, Spotify, Netflix, IBM, and Airbnb as customers, and is going public at a $9 billion enterprise value (EV), would you buy it?
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         What if I told you it\xe2\x80\x99s burning $3.2 billion per year, has historically failed to meet nearly every target it set, and has to do construction every time it wants to increase its inventory? And that it had to pull a planned 2019 IPO due to investor disgust at the founder and CEO\xe2\x80\x99s antics. Would you buy it then?
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         This is the WeWork enigma. It has done some truly mind-blowingly impressive things while burning mountains of Masa\xe2\x80\x99s money. If it weren\xe2\x80\x99t for some huge unforced errors, it would have gone public at a valuation near $50 billion way back in 2019,
         <em>
          before
         </em>
         COVID supersized remote work valuations. It rode a positive narrative to the moon, and came crashing down when the narrative flipped.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         We all know We. The company\xe2\x80\x99s story was everywhere in the fall of 2019. WeWork\xe2\x80\x99s failed IPO was a car crash of epic proportions, and we all rubber necked. As someone who worked for a WeWork competitor, Breather, I watched it all with particular schadenfreude (this is Packy, speaking for myself).
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         But since its public failure, it installed new management, flew under the radar, and refocused on its core business. It\xe2\x80\x99s less exciting, but more solid. Its business model is neither inherently terrible nor is it as high-margin, high-growth as a pure software business.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         When WeWork was private, figuring out WeWork was SoftBank\xe2\x80\x99s problem. We could afford to laugh at the company\xe2\x80\x99s story without thinking too much about the actual business. But now that BowX SPAC\xe2\x80\x99d it at a seemingly reasonable $9 billion valuation on $3 billion in revenue (in this economy?!), it\xe2\x80\x99s worth taking a closer look. Today, we\xe2\x80\x99ll do that:
        </p>
        <ul style="margin: 1em 0;">
         <li style="margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           <strong>
            The Royal We.
           </strong>
           Adam Neumann was narcissistic and brash\xe2\x80\xa6 exactly what was needed to shake up office real estate.
          </p>
         </li>
         <li style="margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           <strong>
            WeStory.
           </strong>
           From 3,000 sq ft in Soho to millions across the world, fueled by an epic hype flywheel.
          </p>
         </li>
         <li style="margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           <strong>
            From WeWork to We.
           </strong>
           Neumann pushed the company outside of office and into a little bit of everything.
          </p>
         </li>
         <li style="margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           <strong>
            IPOh No!
           </strong>
           WeWork\xe2\x80\x99s attempted 2019 IPO failed spectacularly thanks to unforced errors, and the company brought in new management, refocused, and trimmed down.
          </p>
         </li>
         <li style="margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           <strong>
            WeSPAC.
           </strong>
           On Friday,Vivek Ranadiv\xc3\xa9\xe2\x80\x99s BowX SPAC announced that it\xe2\x80\x99s taking WeWork public at a $9 billion valuation.
          </p>
         </li>
         <li style="margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           <strong>
            Side Note: Masa is a Genius Again.
           </strong>
           Masa is on a tear. WeWork breaking even would be the icing on his comeback cake.
          </p>
         </li>
         <li style="margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           <strong>
            WeWork by the Numbers.
           </strong>
           The refocused WeWork is a straightforward business.
          </p>
         </li>
         <li style="margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           <strong>
            The WeWork Bear Case.
           </strong>
           This time, maybe it\xe2\x80\x99s the market\xe2\x80\x99s fault.
          </p>
         </li>
         <li style="margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           <strong>
            The WeWork Bull Case.
           </strong>
           WeWork survived, erased its mistakes, and is perfectly positioned to capture value in a more flexible world.
          </p>
         </li>
         <li style="margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           <strong>
            Back to the Future.
           </strong>
           You know who would have been a perfect CEO for this market?
          </p>
         </li>
        </ul>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Look, no one expected us to be publicly defending Adam Neumann less than we, but here we are.
        </p>
        <h3 style="-moz-osx-font-smoothing: antialiased; -webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased; color: #1a1a1a; font-family: 'SF Compact Display', -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, 'Segoe UI', Roboto, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif, 'Apple Color Emoji', 'Segoe UI Emoji', 'Segoe UI Symbol'; font-size: 1.375em; font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.16em; margin: 1em 0 0.625em 0;">
         <strong>
          The Royal We
         </strong>
        </h3>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Maybe Adam Neumann really was the savior Adam Neumann thought Adam Neumann was.
        </p>
        <div class="captioned-image-container-static" style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin-bottom: 16px; text-align: center;">
         <figure style="display: inline-block; margin: 0 auto; width: 100%;">
          <table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" class="image-wrapper" style="margin: 8px auto; mso-padding-alt: 1em 0 1.6em;" width="100%">
           <tbody>
            <tr>
             <td style="text-align: center;">
             </td>
             <td align="left" class="content" style="text-align: center;" width="550">
              <a class="image-link" href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxVUtuO3CAM_ZrJWyIwl8BDHlaV-hsRF5OJJoEskN1Ov77MpFJVCdnGls-xfOxMxSXl53SkUruXmevzwCnid9mwVszdWTDPq5-oBMUE152fuKdKqG4tc8iIu1m3qeYTu-O02-pMXVN8dxACortPNjCFxjIkhAXjhdXMBpCjoIICB7h4zelXjA4n_ML8TBG7bbrXepQb-7jBz_acj0M5banGPQaX9pZad7Ng8wGru798g6npBj8-r4B9LCn59g_bfOS0ZCxl_cKWLxXxaB0XBYgXiXjRNGNP98BWzz0SYa1TvLfGsJ6zEXstqOqNtwwsjqNWfChsMLv5naL5LtdcDePaxTt8D1neIVfCBENkb4RseEE3PATbE86N0iM6LWHWkvySnA5HXLp1AgKUMNAUxEjHgQ6cgQzBjsZZHZRAJrkXyIPULnjB4MbJvsB_m-ryFFO1Ka9xaeXH3ey4vQttzLn5_Yxrfc4Yjd3QX2rW6yje-s4LRsztWPxsajsFOhIAKYCLv-o1uRlnSnGhu8bsU-uK_0j_AEsFx8g" style="border: none; display: block; height: auto; margin: 0; padding: 0; text-decoration: none; width: auto;" target="_blank">
               <img alt="" class="wide-image" data-attrs='{"src":"https://bucketeer-e05bbc84-baa3-437e-9518-adb32be77984.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/485afa06-a563-4f9e-9e2b-044a897ec962_960x641.png","height":641,"width":960,"resizeWidth":null,"bytes":null,"alt":null,"title":null,"type":null,"href":null}' src="https://cdn.substack.com/image/fetch/w_1920,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fbucketeer-e05bbc84-baa3-437e-9518-adb32be77984.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F485afa06-a563-4f9e-9e2b-044a897ec962_960x641.png" style="-ms-interpolation-mode: bicubic; border: none !important; display: block; height: auto; margin: 0 auto; margin-bottom: 0; max-width: 550px; vertical-align: middle; width: 100%;" width="550"/>
              </a>
             </td>
             <td style="text-align: center;">
             </td>
            </tr>
           </tbody>
          </table>
         </figure>
        </div>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         For the first eight years of WeWork\xe2\x80\x99s life, the We Story was the Adam Neumann story. The two were inextricably linked. He was the Royal We.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         The WeWork co-founder and ex-CEO was a narcissistic cult leader who made off with billions and left employees and investors holding the bag.
        </p>
        <ul style="margin: 1em 0;">
         <li style="margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           He regularly called his direct reports\xe2\x80\x99 direct reports into late-night meetings to publicly embarrass their bosses.
          </p>
         </li>
         <li style="margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           He pushed his co-founder, Miguel McKelvey, aside to give his wife Rebekah more power.
          </p>
         </li>
         <li style="margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           He personally trademarked \xe2\x80\x9cWe\xe2\x80\x9d and sold it back to his own company for $6 million.
          </p>
         </li>
         <li style="margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           He established what is quite possibly the dumbest fucking financial metric in financial metric history:
           <a href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkUuO7CAMRVdTzBKBgXwGDHrythHxMSlUCURAXpTdN1U1aMmyLVtX1zq2uuKa8q2OVCp5p6XeB6qIV9mwVszkLJiX4BQbYOJSzMQp4dgkJxLK4jPirsOmaj6RHKfZgtU1pPhRUAqSPNU8M8dg0JNl1DE2OjpK48HM1s-eyuHrq08XMFpU-B_znSKSTT1rPcqD_zzgX4vrunqzpbQbzGtv095m6Qix2bVO5xrshqW1QNnUUdHB-FbhlfKr09amM9bS-ZQ7m2KxIZ0lYikkKKDAKIeZgRzZ2LNecBi8N6O2ZvaTRD4IJ1H4od3sJIeHoPsKfTlNqdq-3seQrGKqJuUQ17Z-PfWO22fRsCyt7mcM9V4warOh-xKrX_AfhsuKEXN7iFt0bbjZSAEGCULCl1BDygWfJiFn0pxdaqr4Z_oLq4CawA" style="color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">
            Community Adjusted EBITDA
           </a>
           .
          </p>
         </li>
         <li style="margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           He set
           <a href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFUUmOxCAMfE1zIwpblgOHucw3Ihanw3QCETgd5ffDpA8jWQZkymVXOYPwTPnSeypI_tKE1w46wllWQIRMjgJ5Cl6zjg9CyZF4LT0b1EBCmeYMsJmwaswHkP2wa3AGQ4o3om25IouerZOStcIqMIwZcJ2fBWOg1AzWK_nhNYcPEB1oeEO-UgSy6gVxLw_x9eDfNc7zbM7y07i01ZfJGNwKpV5xCYXWiAkpLkBPc9G7i03-ohYW84ZCl3RS481GIxybibHQVP_cAEw7LXitQO0RVqQnnCm_KGOqGwYuBt6ToHnL6xJ8ZFz1rG9YIwXv5tn2xtlxHhSITnoFcu5GN3sl-EO225M35bAFjXv9zU2yrkPalEN81vJrMRusd6FqN9VzO2LAa4Jo7Ar-Iyt-3LmFnp4QIVfX_GSwesL6lvNOcan4R8aqu5BiGKQaSWX2qaLiP-kvODepeQ" style="color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">
            delusional goals
           </a>
           for himself: \xe2\x80\x9cbecoming leader of the world, living forever, amassing more than $1 trillion in wealth.\xe2\x80\x9d
          </p>
         </li>
        </ul>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         But Adam Neumann was also the
         <em>
          <strong>
           perfect
          </strong>
         </em>
         person to launch WeWork, shake up the sleepy commercial real estate industry, and change the way that people rent office space.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Commercial real estate isn\xe2\x80\x99t like software, a fact that critics pointed out over and over again as WeWork\xe2\x80\x99s valuation soared to $47 billion. In the world of bits, a polite, meek coder can spend months locked away in a dark room, emerge with a brilliant piece of software, put it up for sale on a website that anyone can access, and let the market decide whether what they built is worth paying for. It\xe2\x80\x99s pretty close to a meritocracy.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Commercial real estate is an oligopoly. A handful of families, companies, and Real Estate Investment Trusts (REITs) own the vast majority of the desirable real estate in the world\xe2\x80\x99s major metropolises. They own buildings and collect rent checks. Life is pretty good if you own the right piece of real estate, so landlords are not known for being particularly forward thinking or open to change. Polite and meek don\xe2\x80\x99t work in real estate.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Adam Neumann almost sunk his company, but he was also the right person, in the right place, at the right time to get it off the ground in the first place.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         With the benefit of hindsight, it\xe2\x80\x99s easy to say that WeWork should have done all of the good stuff and none of the bad stuff. They should have done revenue share deals with landlords instead of taking on lease obligations. They shouldn\xe2\x80\x99t have thrown big parties. Adam should have been more straightforward and honest.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         But you can\xe2\x80\x99t have your cake and eat it too. A quieter, more conservative WeWork wouldn\xe2\x80\x99t have had the scale, money, shine, or leverage to make a dent in commercial real estate.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         WeWork was the disruptor. Like Napster, it broke some rules. Normally, the disruptor makes a lot of noise, spends a lot of money, and fails. Someone else swoops into a shaken industry, works with landlords, and builds a solid business.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         But in this story, Adam met Masa. SoftBank\xe2\x80\x99s billions both choked WeWork and kept it alive. Adam got the boot, and rightly so. His company, under new management, lives to fight another day.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         What\xe2\x80\x99s unique about this story is that WeWork is both Napster and Spotify. It\xe2\x80\x99s disruptor and partner, destroyer and builder. Somehow, eleven years into the WeWork journey, after a failed IPO attempt and turbulent ups and downs that would make
         <a href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkEuOwyAMhk9TdhMlBhJYsJjNXCPiYVLUhETgtNPbD20XI1m2bMv-7c9bwmUvT3PsldjLzfQ80GR81BWJsLCzYplTMMMIikuhWTAiDEoqluocC-Jm02qonMiO063JW0p7fk_0PUh2Nb3S4Dx460FpVKOS0kUR-OSi01oPH117hoTZo8E7lueeka3mSnTUC_--wE-zx-PR1fQbV7vUzu9bKy0FLdlwx0xnwVawRMX61wW1ZbeUl2C_bpYlAz0MPQc9gJyGqRs6wWGM0U3WOx2VRD6KIFHEUfsYJIeL6LcFunq6StbfXoqsmLyT20vb29q3q91wfTfa63OL25kTPWfM1q0YPlToA_fNaV4wY2nQw2ypIR2mHmCUICR8KDRsXHClhNSsKYe9TeV_0T9R6JJl" style="color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">
          Kingda Ka
         </a>
         jealous, WeWork is going public. It\xe2\x80\x99s in the best position to capture the value created by the destruction it wrought.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         But it all started with 3,000 square feet in Soho.
        </p>
        <h3 style="-moz-osx-font-smoothing: antialiased; -webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased; color: #1a1a1a; font-family: 'SF Compact Display', -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, 'Segoe UI', Roboto, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif, 'Apple Color Emoji', 'Segoe UI Emoji', 'Segoe UI Symbol'; font-size: 1.375em; font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.16em; margin: 1em 0 0.625em 0;">
         <strong>
          WeStory
         </strong>
        </h3>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Just as mobile boomed, the financial markets crashed, and people began working over WiFi on laptops, Neumann and McKelvey launched GreenDesk, an environmentally-conscious co-working space, in Brooklyn\xe2\x80\x99s Dumbo neighborhood in 2008. They quickly realized that green wasn\xe2\x80\x99t the draw, community was, so they sold GreenDesk and launched WeWork in 2010 with 3,000 square feet at 154 Grand Street in Soho. Coincidentally, Packy got coffee at Gasoline Alley in that building every day when Breather\xe2\x80\x99s office was down the street.
        </p>
        <div class="captioned-image-container-static" style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin-bottom: 16px; text-align: center;">
         <figure style="display: inline-block; margin: 0 auto; width: 100%;">
          <table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" class="image-wrapper" style="margin: 8px auto; mso-padding-alt: 1em 0 1.6em;" width="100%">
           <tbody>
            <tr>
             <td style="text-align: center;">
             </td>
             <td align="left" class="content" style="text-align: center;" width="550">
