        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Those investors\xe2\x80\x99 involvement sent a clear signal that WeWork wanted to go public, and that the public markets were waiting with open arms. At the time, institutional investors rarely backed private companies. Instead, T. Rowe, Goldman, and Wellington and other large institutions received allocations in the Initial Public Offering (IPO), and their purchases supported companies\xe2\x80\x99 ability to smoothly enter the public markets. If those IPO experts were in, the logic went, they must believe that WeWork had a good shot as a public company.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         In reality, what it meant is that Adam Neumann\xe2\x80\x99s skills as a salesman extended beyond just local landlords and VCs. He was able to convince some of the world\xe2\x80\x99s most buttoned-up investors that WeWork wasn\xe2\x80\x99t just any real estate company. That, in turn, convinced landlords to lease WeWork more space, which meant more revenue, which got investors excited, which got landlords excited, and so on. Neumann built a Hype Flywheel so strong that it sucked in people typically immune to hype, including
         <a href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkcmO6yAQRb8m7LDMaLNg0Zv3GxZDOaZjIAL8LP99k6SllhgKFbdu6ZQzDe65XPqZa0OvY2nXE3SCs-7QGhR0VChL8JpIOjPBFfKaezKLGYW6rAUgmrDrVg5Az8PuwZkWcnorxpEKtGm7jhOTXo5qsoowBZT0DYquxBFi7cfXHD5AcqDhP5QrJ0C73lp71hv7utF_fZ3nOZz1e3A59pcpLbgdag_bBjh2xYUjJHxuGUMydgePjTcRJziiSQmb5PHr6wlnLg_swZpeABMiJkmVkkSioOlIycioIlRMZBrIwBmV62on46xaZwFMci-Ar1K51QtGb3yMdzrUw9Zm3OPVHSo65WZzCene04_NRNjfiU5o6Xc8UmjX8tvlB177zOCNc7lDgtJn4xfTOnkyjZRKQbmgH1idLuNsnrlQqDv73FXpz_QHhD2eJQ" style="color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">
          Jamie Dimon and WeWork\xe2\x80\x99s board
         </a>
         .
        </p>
