        </div>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         In half a decade, though, Neumann had built the largest coworking company in the world, thrown the traditional five-to-ten-year lease model into question, and raised over $1 billion dollars. His company controlled millions of square feet of office. Given that meteoric rise, it\xe2\x80\x99s understandable that Neumann thought he could do anything.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         It started with WeLive. If coworking worked, why couldn\xe2\x80\x99t coliving? Theoretically, the same principles apply: lease space wholesale, chop it up and add shared amenities, and sell it retail. Plus, maybe if we all lived together, we could cure loneliness and make people happier. In the company\xe2\x80\x99s Series D deck, it said, \xe2\x80\x9cThe demand for Space as a Service extends to residential real estate, making WeLive a natural extension of the WeWork concept, community, and brand.\xe2\x80\x9d
        </p>
